In its simplest form, therefore, matter evinces the desire of reciprocal union, or, as it is commonly called, the attraction of gravitation. Increase its mass,- arrange it in other modifications, and it immediately evinces other powers or attractions and these will be perpetually, and almost in· finitely, varied, in proportion as we vary its combinations.
